(PSL) Boosting¶

AdaBoost¶

Toy Data¶

The feature X is one-dimensional and uniformly generated from the interval [0, 2]. Each data point is then assigned to one of the two classes, with squares representing one class and plus signs representing the other.

The Algorithm¶

The myboosting function is a direct implementation of one iteration of the AdaBoost algorithm, customized for the toy data we've generated. In this dataset, the feature X is one-dimensional and ordered in ascending order: x[1] < x[2] < ... x[n].

The weak classifier g is a simple random classifier. It randomly selects a sample point with an index between 1 to n-1 and predicts 1 for data points to the left of that selected point and -1 for data points to the right of the selected point. More formally, we can write g as follows: suppose the index of the sample point selected by g is m,

  • g(x) = 1 if x < the midpoint between x[m] and x[m+1];
  • g(x) = -1 if x >= the midpoint between x[m] and x[m+1];
In [211]:
import numpy as np

def myboosting(G, w, x, y):
# G: previous committee
# w: previous weight
# x: covariates
# y: response
# g: current classifier, y=1, if x < split

 n = len(x)
 pos = np.random.choice(n-1,1) + 1 
 g = np.concatenate([np.ones(pos), -np.ones(n-pos)])
 err = np.sum((1 - y*g)*w)/2
 alpha = (1/2)*np.log((1 - err)/(err))
 G = G + alpha*g
 w1 = w*np.exp(-alpha*y*g)
 w1 = w1/np.sum(w1)
 return {'G':G, 'w': w, 'w1': w1, 'g': np.sign(alpha)*g, 
         'err': np.minimum(err,1-err), 
         'split': (x[pos-1]+x[pos])/2, 'a': alpha}

The myplot function will be used to provide a visual illustration of AdaBoost.

In [232]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
def myplot(myout, x, y):
  n=len(x)
  m = np.sum(y>0)
  tmp1 = np.vstack([myout['w'].reshape(-1,1),myout['w1'].reshape(-1,1)]).reshape(-1,)
  tmp2 = np.vstack([(x-0.04).reshape(-1,1),x.reshape(-1,1)]).reshape(-1,)
  tmp3 = np.vstack([(5*np.ones(n)).reshape(-1,1),(6*np.ones(n)).reshape(-1,1)]).reshape(-1,)
  mymax = np.max(np.concatenate([myout['w'], myout['w1']]))

  plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
  plt.bar(x-0.04, myout['w'], color = 'blue', width = 0.04);
  plt.bar(x, myout['w1'], color = 'green', width = 0.04);
  plt.xlim([-0.1, 2.3]);
  plt.ylim([-0.04, 0.12]);

  plt.scatter(x[y>0], np.ones(m)*(-mymax/6), marker='+', color = 'black');
  plt.scatter(x[y<0], np.ones(n-m)*(-mymax/6), marker='s', color = 'black');
  plt.scatter([np.max(x)+0.2], [-mymax/6], marker = '$1$', color = 'black', label = 'train');
  
  tmp1 = np.sum(myout['g']>0);
  plt.scatter(x[myout['g']>0], np.ones(tmp1)*(-mymax/3), marker='+', color = 'black');
  plt.scatter(x[myout['g']<0], np.ones(n-tmp1)*(-mymax/3), marker = 's', color = 'black');
  plt.scatter([np.max(x)+0.2], [-mymax/3], marker = '$2$', color = 'black', label = 'current');

  tmp1 = np.sum(np.sign(myout['g'][0])*np.sign(myout['g'])==1)-1
  tmp2 = np.sum((x[tmp1]+x[tmp1+1])/2)
  plt.plot(np.array([tmp2, tmp2]), np.array([-mymax/2, mymax+0.03]), linestyle = 'dashed');

  tmp1 = sum(myout['G']>0);
  plt.scatter(x[myout['G']>0], np.ones(tmp1)*(-mymax/2), marker='+', color = 'black');
  plt.scatter(x[myout['G']<0], np.ones(n-tmp1)*(-mymax/2), marker='s', color = 'black');
  plt.scatter([np.max(x)+0.2], [-mymax/2], marker = '$3$', color = 'black', label = 'overall');
  plt.legend()

Let's discuss the visual representation after one iteration.

  • The blue bars represent the original weights assigned to each data point. Initially, everyone is equally weighted and has the same height.
  • The green bars represent the changes in weight over iterations. When we make mistakes in classification, the purple weights increase. This adjustment process will continue iteratively.

Plot the 0/1 Loss and Exponential Loss from T=200 Boosting Steps¶

In [220]:
T = 200
err = np.ones(T)
exploss = np.zeros(T)
n = len(x)
G = np.zeros(n)
w = np.ones(n)/n
myout = myboosting(G, w, x, y)
err[0] = np.sum(np.sign(myout['G']) != y)/n
exploss[0] = np.sum(np.exp(-y*myout['G']))/n
for i in range(1,T):
  myout = myboosting(myout['G'], myout['w1'], x, y)
  err[i] = np.sum(np.sign(myout['G']) != y)/n
  exploss[i] = np.sum(np.exp(-y*myout['G']))/n
plt.scatter(range(T), err, s = 10, label = 'Error');
plt.scatter(range(T), exploss, s = 10, label = 'Exponential Loss');
plt.legend();
plt.xlabel("Iteration");
plt.ylabel("Training Loss");

Here's an interesting takeaway from this illustration: the training error, represented by the blue dots, does not exhibit a consistent monotonic decrease as the number of iterations (T) increases. It's important to recall that our proof demonstrated that what decreases monotonically is not the actual training error itself but rather its upper bound, which is depicted by the orange dots.

Lastly, it's important to note that the classifier returned by AdaBoost is not guaranteed to perform well on the test data. AdaBoost tends to overfit, so it's essential to implement regularization or early stopping to achieve good generalization on test data.

Early Stopping & Shrinkage¶

Toy Data¶

The true density, denoted as $p(x) = P(Y=1 | X=x)$, is depicted in black on the graph. The ideal classification is shown as well, with blue representing class 0 and red representing class 1. We generated a dataset of 100 training samples from this distribution.

d = 2
test_x = np.arange(1,101)/100
dx = d*test_x - np.floor(d*test_x)
ptest_x = 2*dx*(dx <= 0.5).astype(int) + 2*(1 - dx)*(dx > 0.5).astype(int)
plt.plot(test_x, ptest_x, color = "black");
plt.plot([0,1], [0.5,0.5], color = "red");
plt.plot([0,0.125], [0.5,0.5], color = "blue");
plt.plot([0.375, 0.625], [0.5,0.5], color = "blue");
plt.plot([0.875, 1], [0.5,0.5], color = "blue");

n = 100
x = np.sort(np.random.uniform(size = n))
dx = d*x - np.floor(d*x)
px = 2*dx*(dx <= 0.5).astype(int) + 2*(1 - dx)*(dx > 0.5).astype(int)
y = ((px - np.random.uniform(size = n)) > 0).astype(int) # y is 0/1, not -1/1
plt.scatter(x[y == 1], y[y==1], color = "red", s = 10);
plt.scatter(x[y == 0], y[y==0], color = "blue", s = 10);
plt.xlabel('x');
plt.ylabel('P(Y = 1 | X = x)');

Gradient Boosting¶

Gradient boosting is implemented in GradientBoostingClassifier [Link].

  • Available loss functions are log_loss (Binomial deviance) and exponential (same as AdaBoost)
  • n_estimators: number of boosting iterations (i.e. number of trees)
  • learning_rate: learning rate shrinkage factor
  • subsample: subsample rate for base leaners

we experimented with two different sets of parameters.

  • In the first case, we set shrinkage = 0.1, the default value, highlighting the importance of early stopping to obtain a better estimate of the conditional probability $P(Y=1 | X=x).$
  • In the second case, we reduced the shrinkage factor to 0.001 (which necessitated an increase in the number of trees). These results demonstrate that the shrinkage factor can be helpful in reducing overfitting. The plots also indicates underfitting, so we should increase n_estimators.
In [247]:
from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingClassifier as GBC
from scipy.special import logit
toy_gbm1 = GBC(loss = 'exponential', n_estimators = 500, 
               subsample = 0.5, learning_rate = 0.1).fit(x.reshape(-1,1), y)
staged_preds = np.array([preds for preds in 
                         toy_gbm1.staged_predict_proba(test_x.reshape(-1,1))])
sizes = [2, 50, 100, 500]
fig = plt.figure()
for i in range(len(sizes)):
  plt.subplot(2, 2, i+1)
  plt.scatter(x[y == 1], y[y==1], color = "red", s = 5);
  plt.scatter(x[y == 0], y[y==0], color = "blue", s = 5);
  y_pred = logit(staged_preds[sizes[i]-1,:,1])
  plt.plot(test_x, 1/(1 + np.exp(-2*y_pred)), color = 'green', linewidth = 1)
  plt.plot(x, px, color = "black", linewidth = 1)
  plt.title("# of Iterations = " + str(sizes[i]))
fig.tight_layout()
